diaphragmatic function"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring REM sleep, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete muscle paralysis with preserved diaphragmatic function\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to glycine-mediated inhibition of alpha motor neurons in the spinal cord. This paralysis prevents acting out of dreams while maintaining essential respiratory function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased cerebral blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur during REM sleep as cerebral blood flow increases to levels similar to wakefulness. \u003Cstrong\u003EHigh amplitude delta waves\u003C/strong\u003E are not characteristic of REM sleep, which shows low amplitude, high frequency waves similar to wakefulness, while delta waves characterise slow-wave sleep. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduced heart rate and blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E are not features of REM sleep as both heart rate and blood pressure become variable and often increase during this phase. \u003Cstrong\u003ESuppressed dream activity\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as REM sleep is associated with vivid dreaming and increased brain activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther features of REM sleep include rapid eye movements, increased brain temperature, and irregular breathing patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rapid eye movement (REM) sleep is characterised by muscle atonia due to glycine-mediated inhibition of motor neurons.","Brain activity during REM sleep is similar to wakefulness with high frequency, low amplitude EEG patterns.","REM sleep usually occurs every 90 minutes and comprises 20-25% of total sleep time in adults."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 60; 